/* Origin and ritual status */ Please stick to the text. Firstly, Yang doesn't comment on the "Caste" in the text. Secondly, his study was based in Saran district, Bihar which is not the same as North India. Lastly, he specifically mentions members of the Vaishya Varna, so why would you change that to "Vaishya of Varna System". Yang may be great indologist but his reference should stick to caste only and not determine people's varna with contradictory understanding of the "Varna System" as cited

/* History */ This photo is a part of the "documentation of the ethnography of India" during the British Raj. I am sorry but  "colonial ethnographers are not WP:RS; see Wikipedia:Reliable sources/Noticeboard/Archive 172#Are British Raj ethnographers unreliable?". Secondly, "If you did not create the image, or if you are unable or unwilling to verify its copyright status, do not upload the image." - Wikipedia: Image policy. Sir, with due respect. You are breaking rules to prove yourself right.

Poornia Dhawan's observation were specific to the 18th century time-period and is in the context of the Sikh movement in Punjab. Therefore, it fits well where it is placed now. Secondly, Suresh Kumar's observations about the Khatris are not limited to them being "silk weavers". Please reflect on your bias which goes against Wikipedia's policy of a balanced and neutral point of view. Thanks

WP:Balance/Undue weightage; also corrected some grammatical mistakes such as "extremely long sentences". The quotation on koshti (weaver) in Maharastra is a translation from Marathi publication which is not an appropriate source for Wikipedia. Finally, Yang is talking about Vaishya Varn with apparently very little knowledge about the Varn System. He is clearly not an expert to identify somebody's varna, especially when his definition itself differs from standard Indian definitions on Varn systm
